isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.53) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.20. The models intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.26, p < .001, 95% CI [13.02, 14.04]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.37, p = 0.726, 95% CI [-0.85, 0.59]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.22, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.18, S.E. = 0.49, p < .001, 95% CI [-4.15, -2.22]; Std. beta = -0.81, 95% CI [-1.06, -0.56])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.06, S.E. = 0.70, p = 0.003, 95% CI [-3.44, -0.68]; Std. beta = -0.52, 95% CI [-0.88, -0.17])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
